l, Rutland, England","Markeaton, Derbyshire, England":"Markeaton, Derbyshire, England","Buglawton, Cheshire, England":"Buglawton, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1279–1298":"1279–1298","1275–1337":"1275–1337","1298–1349":"1298–1349","1349":"1349","about 1294":"about 1294","1337":"1337","1279":"1279","1298":"1298","1275":"1275","1290":"1290","Ashwell, Oakham, Rutland, England":"Ashwell, Rutland, England","Markeaton, Derbyshire, England":"Markeaton, Derbyshire, England","Buglawton, Cheshire, England":"Buglawton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":11,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes d'Avesnes was born in 1279, in Buglawton, Cheshire, England. She married Sir Robert Touchet III - Lord of Ashwell about 1294. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1298, in Markeaton, Derbyshire, England, at the age of 19."},"et":{"1279–1298":"1279–1298","1275–1337":"1275–1337","1298–1349":"1298–1349","1349":